author: @FrankLi92
text: What other topics are in the works?! Sneak peek perhaps? I personally am interested in learning what coding in the real work world looks like. Most tutorials seem to handhold you and do something along the lines of "hello world." While not inherently bad, I think it makes me, a student, nervous because I'm not sure what to expect at my first job or internship.   Since you've worked as a programmer before, it would be cool to see you point out things in tutorials that we need to focus on or how something you do in the tutorial might not always be the same as what you see on the job. Maybe you can do a "replica" project of something similar to what you've actually shipped before in your career. I believe that knowing someone who got paid to make something similar would give me a tremendous amount of confidence if I could understand the material. It'll give me a good gauge of where I should be and where I currently am.  For future topics if you haven't already planned them, it'd be awesome to learn data science/ML topics. You're one of the few people who can condense difficult concepts into digestible and sensible bites, so if I'm going to learn it, I really hope it would be you!  Cheers!

text: New subscriber here. I am a self taught programmer with main background in Python. I consider myself to be in between the newb to the intermediate python programmer. I watched a few of the OOP videos and enjoyed them very much. You are easy to understand and you don't put information in your videos that you are not going to discuss and apply in that same video. One of my main issues in finding good tutor using tutorials is that a lot of instructors will talk about something you can do and only give tidbits and then say 'don't worry about that now it will be discussed in a future video', then you have to wait 10 different tutorials later just to get back to that information. It becomes frustrating to get small pieces of information and have no clue what they are talking about only to be told don't worry about it now. I'm hoping to be a patron soon and hoping your content can put me in the path of getting my first programming job. Thank you for all your hard work in putting good content out that is definitely helping.

author: @silvanoteneyck2911
text: Your videos have really helped me out a lot.  I've gone through most of the beginning Python set and am now working on your Flask series.  There are lots of instructional videos out there on programming and python.  I'd like to take a block of this comment section to explain what I think you are doing right because I see so many poorly made videos out there.  First: You talk fast.  Not crazy fast but you enunciate well, you get right to the point and you don't spend any time 'um'ing and 'uh'ing.  Second: You prepare.  Using your prewritten code snippets in lieu of having us watch you slowly type out code is a huge deal.  This makes the videos watchable and even exciting as the material is being delivered at a good rate.  It also keeps the videos short and manageable.  Third: You edit.  It's clear that you take the time to review these videos before you release them.  I only know that because so many YouTubers obviously don't.  Again this keeps the videos to a manageable length while keeping the pace steady enough that I never feel like I'm wasting time.  Fourth:  You know your stuff.  It's also clear you take the time to make sure you know what you are talking about and you organize the material so it is not overwhelming but still a good pace of delivery.  I personally prefer watching the material and listening to staring at someone's head.  But such a conversational style as you put it may be right for certain content.  Congratulations on your YouTube award.  I think you've earned it.  I look forward to your future videos and will continue to enjoy your posted content.  Cheers.

author: @slavoie
text: Corey, you truly are awesome! Having the opportunity to hang around viewing your videos more often now that you are going in full-time means that you will have a positive impact for many, many people... including me for sure! I can only thank you for your kindness, generosity and open attitude. I would consider myself quite broke at the moment and even though I experience some guilt benefiting from your excellent work without giving back for now, you can be assured that you will be the first person I will be spending my money on with Patreon once I can lend a better job (thanks in good part to your great instructional videos!).  I will be more than happy to hear you talk about whatever subject you come up with, but I must be honest: I really hope you will be continuing your journey teaching Python like a pro. I mean, just keep it the way it is! I know there are many resources out there teaching that language, but nobody comes close to the quality you provide. You have a way to go more in depth while keeping the stuff very interesting with real examples and it shows you know what you are doing. You always have snippets ready to explain concepts in a way that suddenly makes more sense!  I hope you will have many more plates coming in the mail... and real silver too, because you deserve it ;).
